<DOC><DOCNO> AP890714-0090 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1049EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-NewsConferenceShooting     07-14 0266</FIRST><SECOND>PM-News Conference Shooting,0273</SECOND><HEAD>Domestic Shooting Provides Prelude To News Conference on Crack</HEAD><DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Reporters gathering in a dilapidatedneighborhood for a news conference about drug abuse watched in shockas a gun battle erupted in an alley across the street.   City Councilman John P. Kennedy had called the news conferenceThursday on a curbside across from some abandoned houses that hesaid were hangouts for crack cocaine dealers.   Kennedy's intention was to dramatize the problem of drug abuse inColumbus. But before he even arrived, ``gunshots and shouting brokeout in an alley just across the street,'' said reporter Jerry Revishof Columbus TV station WBNS.   Reporters immediately focused their attention and cameras on thearea, where a woman was firing a rifle from a fire escape, Revishsaid.   Morris Brown, 29, was taken to St. Anthony Medical Center inColumbus, where he was treated for a gunshot wound in the shoulder,WBNS reported.   Brown was listed in fair condition Thursday night, said a womanat St. Anthony's patient information desk who refused to give hername.   Police were questioning two suspects in the shooting Thursdaynight, authorities told Columbus radio station WTVN. The two had notbeen charged, the station reported.   A woman who answered the telephone at the Columbus Division ofPolice referred calls to the sergeant on duty, who was out of theoffice.   After the shooting, reporters regrouped at the news conferencesite, where Kennedy was just arriving, Revish said.   Kennedy called for the creation of a citywide drug coordinator tohelp fight the battle against drugs.</TEXT></DOC>